{"parentUuid":"e94e7546-dedb-487b-9915-fd4ba3737221","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/skogix/.local/share/containers","sessionId":"b9e8251b-c2cb-4ad4-b79e-9eb7c996b007","version":"2.1.62","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"rosy-whistling-horizon","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BukraFvwc84P3iUrEJH4fj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so I need to design this properly for scale - 200-300 services, containers, and VMs. Let me think about this seriously.\n\nKey design considerations:\n- Scale: 200-300 services/containers/VMs\n- Multiple types: containers (podman), VMs (probably libvirt/QEMU), possibly compose stacks\n- Need dynamic choice functions to discover services\n- Need consistent interface across service types\n\nLet me think about the submenu layout:\n\nTop level should be generic operations that work across all service types:\n```\nargc\n├── list                    # all managed services\n├── up <service>            # start any service\n\n\n├── down <service>          # stop any service\n├── status <service>        # status of any service\n└── <service-name>          # per-service namespace\n    ├── <service>::up\n    ├── <service>::down\n    ├── <service>::logs\n    └── <service>::shell\n```\n\nBut wait - with 200-300 services, hardcoding a namespace for each one would bloat the Argcfile beyond reason. I need to flip this approach entirely: services should be discovered dynamically through choice functions rather than statically defined. The Argcfile stays lean while the interface remains flexible across all service types.\n\nSo instead of per-service namespaces, I'll have generic top-level commands that work with any discovered service, plus type-specific namespaces for operations unique to containers, VMs, or other service categories. This way the command structure scales without exploding the configuration file. I'm sketching out the command structure with generic operations at the top level that work across all service types, then type-specific namespaces below for container, VM, and compose-specific operations. The key insight is that with hundreds of services, they need to be discovered dynamically from the filesystem rather than hardcoded into the Argcfile.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the full design scope: I need to map out the input/output interfaces for each command, define how services get discovered from podman, virsh, and the filesystem, and then create a flow diagram showing how everything connects together.\n\nFor scaling to hundreds of services, the key insight is that generic commands should accept service names as arguments rather than creating individual commands per service—the dynamic choice functions validate which services exist and what type they are, while type-specific operations stay in their own namespaces.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1167,"cache_read_input_tokens":68111,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1167},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CYagaesiun83ABPoWmMGC","type":"assistant","uuid":"a0f9cd16-c793-4457-8ee2-1c8be14b7f94","timestamp":"2026-02-28T15:13:17.877Z"}
{"parentUuid":"a0f9cd16-c793-4457-8ee2-1c8be14b7f94","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/skogix/.local/share/containers","sessionId":"b9e8251b-c2cb-4ad4-b79e-9eb7c996b007","version":"2.1.62","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"rosy-whistling-horizon","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BukraFvwc84P3iUrEJH4fj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Step 1: Submenu Layout\n\n200-300 services rules out per-service namespaces in the Argcfile. Services must be discovered, not hardcoded. Two layers: **generic** (works on anything by name) and **type-specific** (operations unique to that runtime).\n\n```\nargc\n│\n├── list [--type]            # all managed services, optionally filtered\n├── up <service>             # start any service by name\n├── down <service>           # stop any service by name\n├── logs <service> [-f]      # logs for any service\n├── shell <service>          # shell into any service\n├── status <service>         # status of any service\n│\n├── container                # podman-specific ops\n│   ├── container::list\n│   ├── container::up <name>\n│   ├── container::down <name>\n│   ├── container::logs <name> [-f]\n│   └── container::shell <name>\n│\n└── vm                       # libvirt/qemu-specific ops\n    ├── vm::list\n    ├── vm::up <name>\n    ├── vm::down <name>\n    └── vm::console <name>\n```\n\n---\n\n## Step 2: Input/Output Interfaces\n\n| Command | Input | Output |\n|---|---|---|\n| `list` | `--type [container\\|vm\\|compose]` (optional) | table: name, type, status |\n| `up <service>` | `service` (choice fn) | status line |\n| `down <service>` | `service` (choice fn) | status line |\n| `logs <service>` | `service` (choice fn), `-f` flag | stdout passthrough |\n| `shell <service>` | `service` (choice fn) | interactive tty |\n| `status <service>` | `service` (choice fn) | status block |\n| `container::*` | `name` (choice fn scoped to containers only) | same as generic |\n| `vm::*` | `name` (choice fn scoped to vms only) | same as generic |\n\n---\n\n## Step 3: Dynamic Choice Functions\n\nServices discovered from filesystem — each service is a directory under `~/.local/share/containers/` with a manifest file declaring its type and runtime config.\n\n```\n_choice_service          # all services (reads manifest dirs)\n_choice_container        # containers only\n_choice_vm               # vms only\n_choice_type             # static: container | vm | compose\n```\n\n`_choice_service` scans `$CONTAINERS_DIR/*/manifest.toml`, extracts name. Scoped variants filter by `type =` field in manifest.\n\n---\n\n## Step 4: Flow — Beginning to End\n\n```\nargc up searxng\n│\n├── argc validates \"searxng\" against _choice_service output\n├── resolves type from manifest.toml → \"container\"\n├── dispatches to _run_container_up \"searxng\"\n│   ├── reads manifest.toml for image, ports, volumes, env\n│   ├── checks if container exists → start vs run\n│   └── prints status line\n└── exit 0\n```\n\n```\nargc logs searxng -f\n│\n├── validates \"searxng\" against _choice_service\n├── resolves type → \"container\"\n├── dispatches to _run_container_logs \"searxng\" [follow=1]\n│   └── podman logs [-f] searxng\n└── exit 0\n```\n\n**Manifest drives everything** — the Argcfile never hardcodes a service name or config value. Adding a new service = drop a `manifest.toml` in its directory.\n\n---\n\nReady for someone else to implement. What's the `manifest.toml` schema — define it now or leave that to the implementer?"}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1167,"cache_read_input_tokens":68111,"output_tokens":2119,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1167,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CYagaesiun83ABPoWmMGC","type":"assistant","uuid":"4f39