{"parentUuid":"2aa043a7-9263-415b-a9b9-1bd9a3d1171d","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/skogix/.local/src/container","sessionId":"b9e8251b-c2cb-4ad4-b79e-9eb7c996b007","version":"2.1.62","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"rosy-whistling-horizon","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SoCjR62qjosHzidUrpWr3U","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a full picture. Let me synthesize what I know and write the design spec plan.\n\nKey insight from the exploration:\n- `run-script.sh` converts JSON `{\"action\": \"up\", \"follow\": true}` → `--action up --follow` → calls `./scripts/searxng.sh --action up --follow`\n- BUT our scripts currently have `# @arg action![up|down|logs|shell]` which is a POSITIONAL arg, not `--action` option\n- The `run-script.sh` always converts to flags (`--key value`), so scripts need `@option` or `@flag` annotations, NOT `@arg` for things like action\n\n\n- When `run-script.sh` invokes the script directly with `eval`, argc parses those flag-style arguments against the script's annotations, so I need to define `--action` as an option and `--follow` as a flag for this to work properly.\n- But `argc run` calls the script with positional arguments instead (`main up -f`), which is a completely different interface.\n- I'm realizing these two calling conventions are fundamentally incompatible—either the script needs to accept both styles, or one of the callers needs to be adapted to match the other's convention. The core issue is that the user wants both calling conventions to work—the argc-style flag approach and the positional argument approach. The simplest fix would be to restructure the scripts using `@describe` with `@option` flags instead of `@arg` positional arguments, then update the argc dispatcher to convert commands into the appropriate flag-based calls. I see the bigger picture now—the argc annotations act as a dual-purpose schema that works for both human CLI usage and future AI agent integration through `run-script.sh`. Since `run-script.sh` always generates `--key value` style arguments from JSON, all script parameters need to be defined as `@option` flags rather than positional `@arg` parameters to maintain consistency across both interfaces.\n\nLooking at the current searxng.sh implementation, it's structured incorrectly with `@cmd` on the main function and positional `@arg` for the action parameter, so I need to refactor it to use the `@describe` and `@option --action` pattern instead. The Argcfile.sh already handles passing `argc_args` through properly, so once the individual scripts are aligned with this pattern, `skog argc run searxng --action up` will work seamlessly. Beyond the script interface fixes, I also need to think through the service configuration approach for managing 300+ services and establish a shared library for the actual container operations. I'm realizing the `run()` function in Argcfile.sh shouldn't pass `main` as the first argument either, since the script uses `@describe` style without a subcommand requirement. So it should just pass the argc args directly to the script, and then `skog argc run searxng --action up` would work correctly by forwarding those arguments through.\n\nFor completion, the `_choice_scripts_args` function would need to adapt to how `@describe` style scripts handle arguments, but I'll set that aside for now and focus on the core plan: converting all 22 scripts from the `@cmd main` pattern with `@arg action` to using `@describe` with `@option --action`, updating the Argcfile's `run()` function to drop the `main` prefix, and organizing service configurations in a TOML manifest structure under the `services/` directory.\n\nNow I'm realizing I should verify whether switching to `@option` is actually necessary. The `run-script.sh` converts JSON input into command-line flags, and looking at how it transforms the data—arrays become repeated flags, booleans become flag names, and strings/numbers become key-value pairs—there's no mechanism to create positional arguments from JSON. This means any parameter that needs to come from the JSON input absolutely requires `@option` syntax, not `@arg`.\n\nThe real tension is that `@arg` works fine for direct CLI calls like `skog argc run searxng up`, but it breaks the JSON path. The cleanest approach is to standardize everything on `@option` throughout—so the CLI invocation becomes `skog argc run searxng --action up` instead. It's slightly less intuitive for direct CLI usage, but it keeps both paths consistent and lets the completion system work properly. Looking at how `port.sh` uses `@option --port![...]`, this pattern is already established in the codebase, so I should follow that convention.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3143,"cache_read_input_tokens":111065,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3143},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CYatPm58oG6EFo9NtGywj","type":"assistant","uuid":"efd36e79-e25f-49a1-9e94-64dc20c461d8","timestamp":"2026-02-28T17:48:32.701Z"}
