{"parentUuid":"1e7c5e00-e46f-4f96-8c74-33183a2a2319","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/skogix/.local/share/containers","sessionId":"b9e8251b-c2cb-4ad4-b79e-9eb7c996b007","version":"2.1.62","gitBranch":"master","slug":"rosy-whistling-horizon","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"1. well yes and no. `@option --action` makes absolutely 100% sense in a way. what dont make sense is strict types for AI agents IO. no matter how much i'd live it - your input and output as a LLM is literally tokens/string -> tokens/string and that is true for the MCP protocol as well.   \n\nwhat i wanted to show was this:\n\n```\n./utils/build-declarations.sh scripts/searxng.sh\n[\n  {\n    \"name\": \"main\",\n    \"description\": \"SearXNG container management\",\n    \"parameters\": {\n      \"type\": \"object\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"action\": {\n          \"type\": \"string\",\n          \"description\": \"Action to perform\",\n          \"enum\": [\n            \"up\",\n            \"down\",\n            \"logs\",\n            \"shell\"\n          ]\n        },\n        \"follow\": {\n          \"type\": \"boolean\",\n          \"description\": \"Follow log output (logs only)\"\n        }\n      },\n      \"required\": []\n    }\n  }\n]\n```\n \n\nthe reason for \"option\" is twofold; 1: named input params helps with json and stupid MCP-protocols 2: stupid MCP and AI Agents really hate null - which means \"options in skogai ALWAYS have a default value or `\"\"`\". and we create json declrarations from both kinds of invocations, shell scripts, javascripts, python and literally everything you can think of. *SO WHAT WE NEED FROM YOU IS WHAT I ASKED IN STEP 1*: WHAT INPUT AND OUTPUT DO WE NEED TO COVER EVERY CASE EXISTING AS WELL AS HOW DO YOU WANT TO CALL IT AND STRUCTURE IT!? "},"uuid":"12338c1e-30e7-4f42-a6db-4bb76e84db0a","timestamp":"2026-02-28T18:19:43.283Z","permissionMode":"acceptEdits"}
{"parentUuid":"12338c1e-30e7-4f42-a6db-4bb76e84db0a","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/skogix/.local/share/containers","sessionId":"b9e8251b-c2cb-4ad4-b79e-9eb7c996b007","version":"2.1.62","gitBranch":"master","slug":"rosy-whistling-horizon","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013VeBkWEZN9tzcQCxznKAhn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK now I understand the full picture. The user is showing me that `utils/build-declarations.sh` generates JSON schema from argc annotations. This is the key - the argc annotations become:\n1. CLI argument parsing\n2. JSON schema for MCP/AI agents\n3. Function declarations for tool calling\n\nThe user is asking me to do Step 1 and Step 2 properly:\n1. What is the submenu/command structure?\n2. What inputs and outputs do we need for EVERY case?\n\nThe key insight about `@option`:\n- Named params → JSON properties\n- Always need defaults or `\"\"` (no nulls for MCP/AI agents)\n- The same script serves CLI, MCP, AI agents, run-script.sh\n\n\n- Now I'm mapping out the actual interface - containers have actions like `up`, `down`, `logs`, `shell`, `status`, and `restart`, while VMs would use `console` instead of shell/logs. For the input parameters, `up` doesn't need extra params since the config comes from the service definition.\n\nFor `logs` I'd add `--follow` and `--lines` flags, `shell` needs `--user` and `--cmd` options, while `down` and `status` require nothing extra. All output goes to `$LLM_OUTPUT` in a structured format that's both human and AI-readable - `status` returns a simple string like `running` or `stopped`, while `logs` outputs raw content and `up`/`down` give confirmation messages. The key principle is that every option must have a sensible default value. I'm realizing the distinction now—`@flag` creates a boolean that the agent can omit entirely, but `@option` without a default becomes `null` when missing, which the user wants to avoid. So I need to give all options explicit defaults, like `--follow=false` for the boolean option, while flags can remain optional. Let me reconsider the structure for organizing these scripts with submenus. the scripts themselves)\n\nEach script needs ONE command: `main`. But what does `main` expose?\n\nOption A: Single `--action` discriminator\n```bash\n# @describe Grafana dashboard\n# @option --action=[up|down|logs|status]\n# @option --follow=false\n# @option --lines=100\nmain() { ... }\n```\n\nOption B: Multiple commands in one script\n```bash\n# @cmd up\nup() { ... }\n# @cmd down  \ndown() { ... }\n# @cmd logs\n# @flag -f --follow\nlogs() { ... }\n```\n\nBut Option B doesn't work with `run-script.sh` which always calls the script directly (no subcommand). And Option B uses `@cmd` not `@describe`.\n\nActually wait - the JSON output shows `\"name\": \"main\"` - so the function name becomes the tool name in the schema. If we had multiple commands, we'd get multiple tool entries.\n\nSince `run-script.sh` calls `./scripts/searxng.sh $args` directly without a subcommand, and the user said the Argcfile.sh run() function passes everything through as-is, the structure has to be: one script per service with a single `main()` function and `@describe`, all options declared flat. That means `--action` would be the discriminator inside `main()`.\n\nSo the real question is what input interface every service script should declare—what standard options and flags apply across all of them?\n\nLooking at the five use cases (human CLI, AI agent MCP tool, direct script call, run-script.sh, tab completion), the script needs `@describe` at the top level, `@option` declarations with defaults (never null), `@flag` for booleans, and environment variable handling.\n\nFor the standard service interface, I'm settling on a pattern where `--action` is a required parameter with specific allowed values like `up`, `down`, `logs`, `shell`, or `status`. The question is whether to make it truly required in the schema or give it a sensible default like `status`. Since the user specified options always need defaults, I could use an empty string as the default, but that creates a mismatch with the actual requirement that action must be one of the valid values. you always need to specify what you want to do. So maybe `action!` (required) is fine? The JSON shows `\"required\": []` currently, which is empty. If we make it required it would be in the required array.\n\nLet me look at what the user showed:\n```json\n\"required\": []\n```\n\nSo currently no required fields. The user said \"options always have a default\". So `--action` should have a default or be optional. If it has a default of `\"\"`, then the implementation needs to handle the empty case gracefully.\n\nBut what's the RIGHT design? The user is asking ME to decide.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is giving `--action` a sensible default like `status` — it's safe with no side effects and gives useful output when omitted. I'd use the argc syntax to set that default, so running the command without specifying an action just shows the current status. For the output format, I need something that works for both humans reading the terminal and AI agents parsing it, so I'll use simple key-value lines like `status: running` or `stopped: grafana` depending on the action, with logs just returning raw output.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the actual script structure — each service gets its own script file with a single main function and flat options, and I need to define how input and output work consistently across all of them. The input should be standardized with the action option, a follow flag for streaming logs, and an output channel variable. For the choice functions that list available scripts, I should just enumerate the script files by their stem without any filtering.\n\nThe key design decisions that matter are setting a sensible default action like status, ensuring every option has a value to avoid nulls, and establishing an output format that both humans and AI agents can parse — with the LLM_OUTPUT environment variable serving as the contract for where results get written.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2965,"cache_read_input_tokens":140377,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2965},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CYavqEJfVmNA8s5Uae1QR","type":"assistant","uuid":"15a068f7-087f-430e-bee6-8f8626f60833","timestamp":"2026-02-28T18:20:41.671Z"}
{"parentUuid":"15a068f7-087f-430e-bee6-8f8626f60833","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/skogix/.local/share/containers","sessionId":"b9e8251b-c2cb-4ad4-b79e-9eb7c996b007","version":"2.1.62","gitBranch":"master","slug":"rosy-whistling-horizon","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013VeBkWEZN9tzcQCxznKAhn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I understand. `build-declarations.sh` generates JSON schema from argc annotations. The script IS the schema. Let me actually design the interface properly.\n\n---\n\n## Step 1: Layout\n\nOne `main()` per script. `@describe` at the top. Flat — no subcommands, no nesting. Every service gets the same shape.\n\n```\nscripts/\n  searxng.sh\n  grafana.sh\n  ...\n```\n\n---\n\n## Step 2: Input/Output interface\n\n**Every script declares the same standard set:**\n\n```\n--action  [=status|up|down|logs|shell]   default: status (safe, non-destructive)\n--follow  flag / bool                    default: false\n--lines   string                         default: \"100\"\n--user    string                         default: \"root\"\n```\n\nReasoning per field:\n- `--action` defaults to `status` — AI agents can call with `{}` and get useful info back, never accidentally start/stop something\n- `--follow` is a flag so JSON gets `true/false`, never null\n- `--lines` and `--user` are strings with defaults — never null, MCP stays happy\n- No required fields → `\"required\": []` → AI agent can call with empty `{}`\n\n**Output:**\n\nEverything written to `$LLM_OUTPUT`. Format: plain lines, one fact per line. AI reads tokens, humans read text — same format serves both.\n\n```\nstatus: running\nimage:  docker.io/searxng/searxng:latest\nport:   8888\nuptime: 2 hours\n```\n\n---\n\n## Step 3: Choice functions\n\n`_choice_scripts` — stem names from `scripts/`. Nothing else. No grep, no validation.\n\n`_choice_scripts_args` — `argc --argc-compgen` against the chosen script. The script's own declarations drive completion. Zero maintenance.\n\n---\n\n## Step 4: Flow\n\n```\nInput: skog argc run searxng --action up\n         OR\n       {\"action\": \"up\"}  via run-script.sh\n         OR\n       MCP tool call:    main(action=\"up\")\n         ↓\nAll three resolve to:\n       ./scripts/searxng.sh --action up\n         ↓\n       argc_action=up, argc_lines=100, argc_user=root, argc_follow=0\n         ↓\n       main() sources services/searxng.env\n         ↓\n       delegates to lib/ based on argc_action\n         ↓\n       writes to $LLM_OUTPUT\n         ↓\nOutput: plain lines → terminal / AI token stream / MCP response\n```\n\nSingle convergence point. Schema lives in the script. Declarations are the contract."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2965,"cache_read_input_tokens":140377,"output_tokens":3102,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2965,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CYavqEJfVmNA8s5Uae1QR","type":"assistant","uuid":"5ec3ec9e-32f6-4aca-9d66-923088a0259f","timestamp":"2026-02-28T18:20:53.479Z"}
